"```sql\nSELECT \n    AVG(CASE WHEN c.Segment = 'SME' THEN ym.Consumption ELSE NULL END) - \n    AVG(CASE WHEN c.Segment = 'LAM' THEN ym.Consumption ELSE NULL END) AS SME_vs_LAM,\n    AVG(CASE WHEN c.Segment = 'LAM' THEN ym.Consumption ELSE NULL END) - \n    AVG(CASE WHEN c.Segment = 'KAM' THEN ym.Consumption ELSE NULL END) AS LAM_vs_KAM,\n    AVG(CASE WHEN c.Segment = 'KAM' THEN ym.Consumption ELSE NULL END) - \n    AVG(CASE WHEN c.Segment = 'SME' THEN ym.Consumption ELSE NULL END) AS KAM_vs_SME\nFROM \n    yearmonth ym\nJOIN \n    customers c ON ym.CustomerID = c.CustomerID\nWHERE \n    ym.Date BETWEEN '201301' AND '201312'\nGROUP BY \n    c.Segment\nHAVING \n    ym.Consumption = MIN(ym.Consumption)\n```\n\nThis SQL query calculates the differences in annual average consumption for the year 2013 between different customer segments (SME, LAM, and KAM) for customers with the least amount of consumption paid in CZK. It uses the `yearmonth` and `customers` tables, considering the foreign key relationship between them. The query filters the data for the year 2013 and calculates the average consumption for each segment, then computes the differences as specified in the question."